is array is 6 (The numbers 1, 10, 12, 13, 21, and 31).\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [2,2,2]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: After including the reverse of each number, the resulting array is [2,2,2,2,2,2].\nThe number of distinct integers in this array is 1 (The number 2).\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n1 <= nums[i] <= 106\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def countDistinctIntegers(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countDistinctIntegers(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Create a set to store distinct integers\n        distinct_integers = set(nums)\n        \n        # Function to reverse the digits of a number\n        def reverse_number(n: int) -> int:\n            return int(str(n)[::-1])\n        \n        # Add the reversed numbers to the set\n        for num in nums:\n            distinct_integers.add(reverse_number(num))\n        \n        # The size of the set is the number of distinct integers\n        return len(distinct_integers)\n```\n\nThis solution works as follows:\n1. We initialize a set `distinct_integers` with the original numbers from the input list `nums`. Using a set automatically handles duplicates.\n2. We define a helper function `reverse_number` that takes an integer, converts it to a string, reverses the string, and converts it back to an integer.\n3. We iterate over each number in the original list `nums`, reverse it using the `reverse_number` function, and add the reversed number to the set `distinct_integers`.\n4. Finally, we return the size of the set `distinct_integers`, which represents the number of distinct integers in the final array.", "estimated_date": 1665878400000}